Google Maps itself does not have a specific "time travel" endpoint in its API. However, if you're referring to the Historical Imagery feature from Google Earth, it is not openly available via an API like the Google Maps APIs. The historical imagery feature allows users to see past images of a location, often used for research or presentation purposes.

Currently, Google Maps API provides functionalities primarily revolving around geolocation services like directions, places, routes, etc. There is no direct API endpoint for retrieving historical imagery or a "time travel" feature.

If you're looking for similar capabilities or something specific, you could explore using:

- **Google Maps JavaScript API**: For mapping and routing.
- **Google Earth Engine**: For environmental data analysis and historical imagery, but this is more oriented toward researchers and requires a different approach.

If you're looking for geolocation data, here's an example code snippet using the Google Maps JavaScript API that shows how you would initialize and display a map:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <title>Simple Map</title>
    <script src="https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/js?key=YOUR_API_KEY"></script>
    <script>
      function initMap() {
        // The location of the target you want to visualize
        const location = { lat: -34.397, lng: 150.644 };
        // The map, centered at the location
        const map = new google.maps.Map(document.getElementById("map"), {
          zoom: 8,
          center: location,
        });
        // The marker, positioned at the location
        const marker = new google.maps.Marker({
          position: location,
          map: map,
        });
      }
    </script>
  </head>
  <body onload="initMap()">
    <div id="map" style="height: 500px; width: 100%;"></div>
  </body>
</html>
```

Replace `YOUR_API_KEY` with your actual Google Maps API key. This simple example initializes a map and places a marker at a specified location, but it does not encompass any time travel or historical imagery functionality as suggested initially.

For any specific feature or reference to historical imagery, please check Google Earth’s documentation or their help resources to see if they have made any advancements in their API offerings.
